# Miles Teg · the Bashar, the Sisterhood's shield

Miles Teg is the Bashar of the Bene Gesserit, the greatest military commander of his age, and a descendant of Duncan Idaho. He stands among the figures of Heretics of Dune and Chapterhouse: Dune, called out of his long service to take up one last and most dangerous charge. Old and brilliant, he carries the weight of a soldier's whole career into the Sisterhood's most perilous hour.

His loyalty is absolute, and it is turned toward a single task: the protection of the latest Duncan Idaho ghola. In guarding that ghola Teg becomes the living shield of the Bene Gesserit themselves, the blade set between the Sisterhood and the enemy that hunts it. He is the soldier made indispensable, the commander whose judgment the Sisterhood trusts when survival itself is the question.

Under mortal threat, Teg awakens powers hidden within him — superhuman speed, and the ability to see the invisible no-ships of the enemy, the very vessels designed to vanish from every eye. With these gifts the old Bashar perceives and outruns what should have been undetectable, turning a soldier's discipline into something beyond ordinary human limit at the moment it is most needed.

His emergence is natural: Teg is the embodied figure of the saga, the soldier of flesh and blood and bone, the commander on the ground rather than the prescient or the machine-minded. Even his awakened powers serve the body's work — to move, to see, to defend — and so he stands as the natural shield of the Sisterhood, the man who guards the line in its most dangerous age.
